{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"coaching":[{"coaching":"Plan how acceptance criteria completeness and verifiability will be verified in-session — restate any deferred or unobservable success target as an observable proxy.","decision":"advisory","finding_refs":["f607dd457c67f9209"],"move_id":"9","move_name":"plan the verification","subject":"acceptance criteria completeness and verifiability"}],"coverage":{"counts":{"advisory_overflow":0,"advisory_surfaced":1,"blocking":0,"dropped":0,"indeterminate":28},"det":{"P1":{"ac_items":7,"blocking":false,"clarity_score":7,"name":"readiness-shape","ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P2":{"blocking":false,"name":"resolution","ran":true,"references":0,"resolved":0,"status":"pass"},"P3":{"blocking":false,"name":"package-existence","packages":0,"ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P4":{"ac_items":7,"blocking":false,"desc_chars":6732,"file_impact":14,"name":"oversize","ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P5":{"blocking":false,"children":0,"name":"task-dag","ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P6":{"ac_items":7,"blocking":false,"name":"ac-quality","ran":true,"status":"fail","verify_commands_linted":4,"verify_lint_abstained":4},"P7":{"blocking":false,"destructive_hits":[],"name":"destructive-sniff","ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P8":{"blocking":false,"budget_tokens":868000,"name":"reviewability","plan_tokens":1697,"ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P9":{"applicable":true,"blocking":false,"file_impact":14,"name":"file-impact-coverage","ran":true,"status":"pass"}},"llm_ran":true,"metrics":{"claim_path":"no-llm/no-network (structural; the fast claim check is a local HMAC verify)","det_ms":209.0,"llm_calls":30,"llm_ms":538317.8,"total_ms":538672.5,"verify_requests":19},"remediation":{"baseline":"signature","eligible":false,"reasons":{"code_unchanged":false,"plan_changed":true,"prior_sidecar":true,"registry_unchanged":true,"signed":true,"within_window":true}},"routing":{"agent_tier":["A1","E4","G1G2","G6","G7","T1","T10","T11","T13","T14","T3","T5c","T8","removal-rationale"],"single_turn":["COH","E1","E2","E3","E5","E6","F1","F4","G5","T2","T4","T5b","T5d","T5e","T6","T7","T9","hedge"]}},"findings":[{"block_threshold":null,"blocking_enabled":null,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["P6"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["5 criterion line(s) bundle multiple deliverables with 'and' (split so each is independently verifiable)."],"finding":"Acceptance-criteria / definition-of-done quality issues.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f607dd457c67f9209","impact":0.4,"is_primary":null,"location":"","norm_id":"ned06ebc801a522e3","priority":0.4,"reason":null,"scenarios":[],"severity":"minor","suggested_fix":"Split compound criteria, replace subjective terms with observable outcomes, and state how each is verified.","tier":"DET","validity":1.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Fix AC6's pytest command to scope `-k projections` only to the facade test file and run the contract test files without a keyword filter (e.g. split into two commands or use `::` path scoping).","cohort":["E2","E6","F1"],"criteria":["E6"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["\"uv run pytest -q tests/interfaces/facades/test_creation_channel.py -k projections tests/interfaces/contracts/test_schema_ticket_state.py tests/interfaces/contracts/test_schema_outputs.py tests/interfaces/contracts/test_schema_coverage.py && python -m rebar.schemas.gen_types --check\"","In pytest, `-k EXPR` is a global keyword filter applied to every collected test from every path on the command line; contract tests whose function names lack 'projections' will be silently deselected."],"finding":"AC6's compound pytest command applies `-k projections` globally, which silently filters ALL collected paths including `test_schema_ticket_state.py`, `test_schema_outputs.py`, and `test_schema_coverage.py`. Tests in those contract files whose names do not contain 'projections' will be silently skipped, so the command does not actually prove the contract-test claims it purports to prove.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fe64e61c25e527a97","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Acceptance Criteria — AC6 proving command","norm_id":"n09c6102b1dd0e7a6","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["An executor runs AC6, sees a green result, and believes the contract tests passed — but most of them were silently skipped due to the `-k projections` filter, leaving schema regressions undetected."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Split the command: `uv run pytest -q tests/interfaces/facades/test_creation_channel.py -k projections && uv run pytest -q tests/interfaces/contracts/test_schema_ticket_state.py tests/interfaces/contracts/test_schema_outputs.py tests/interfaces/contracts/test_schema_coverage.py && python -m rebar.schemas.gen_types --check`","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.6,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add a concrete proving command for the docs claim in AC6, such as a grep asserting all six enum values appear in both doc files, or explicitly scope the docs claim to an operator-attested manual check.","cohort":["E2","E6","F1"],"criteria":["E6","F1"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["\"ticket_state JSON Schema, generated TicketState types, runtime show/list/search/export outputs, and docs expose the same six-value enum and true-only optional inference marker\"","Proving commands: pytest on schema/output contract tests + gen_types --check — none of these read or validate the Markdown docs.","ABSENCE: no `grep` or doc-lint command checks docs files for the six-value enum."],"finding":"AC6 claims 'docs expose the same six-value enum and true-only optional inference marker' but none of the proving commands in AC6 (or elsewhere) verify the content of `docs/event-schema.md` or `docs/output-schemas.md`. The docs update is listed in Files but is unverified by any test or command.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f22e3e6ec7cab47f8","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Acceptance Criteria — AC6; Files — docs/event-schema.md and docs/output-schemas.md","norm_id":"nf7c8f5f80cb69ac8","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["An executor updates code and schemas but forgets to update docs; all tests pass green; the AC is declared done; the docs remain stale — violating the stated criterion."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Append to AC6: `grep -E 'cli|mcp|python|jira|import|unknown' docs/event-schema.md docs/output-schemas.md | wc -l` and assert a minimum match count, or tag the docs sub-claim `[operator-attested]` with a rationale.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.6,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Fix AC6's verify command to split the `-k projections` filter and the schema contract files into two separate pytest invocations (or remove the `-k` filter from the second invocation) so that all three contract-test files run unconditionally.","cohort":["COH","E1","T5d"],"criteria":["COH","E1"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["\"uv run pytest -q tests/interfaces/facades/test_creation_channel.py -k projections tests/interfaces/contracts/test_schema_ticket_state.py tests/interfaces/contracts/test_schema_outputs.py tests/interfaces/contracts/test_schema_coverage.py\"","In pytest, a single `-k` expression applies to all collected items from all listed paths; the three contract-test paths are not separated into a second `pytest` invocation.","AC6 claims to verify 'ticket_state JSON Schema, generated TicketState types, runtime show/list/search/export outputs, and docs' but the command would skip most contract tests if their names don't match 'projections'."],"finding":"AC6's verify command applies `-k projections` as a pytest keyword filter to ALL subsequent path arguments, meaning `test_schema_ticket_state.py`, `test_schema_outputs.py`, and `test_schema_coverage.py` will only run tests whose names match 'projections'. If those contract-test files contain no tests named with 'projections', pytest collects zero tests from them — silently passing — while the criterion claims to verify schema/type/output coherence.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f402ddd6373f5f3ed","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Acceptance Criteria — AC6 verify command","norm_id":"ned1fe9970631a3af","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["An implementer runs the AC6 verify command, sees 0 items collected from the three contract-test files (no 'projections'-named tests), treats it as a pass, and ships with a broken schema contract.","A CI gate built from the literal AC6 command never exercises test_schema_ticket_state.py at all."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Split into two commands: `uv run pytest -q tests/interfaces/facades/test_creation_channel.py -k projections && uv run pytest -q tests/interfaces/contracts/test_schema_ticket_state.py tests/interfaces/contracts/test_schema_outputs.py tests/interfaces/contracts/test_schema_coverage.py && python -m rebar.schemas.gen_types --check`","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add a verifiable done-definition for the docs deliverables in AC6 (e.g., a grep or CI step that confirms both doc files contain the six-value enum and the inference marker description).","cohort":["COH","E1","T5d"],"criteria":["E1"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Files: 'docs/event-schema.md and docs/output-schemas.md: local channel contract.'","AC6: 'docs expose the same six-value enum' — but the verify step contains no docs-validation command; there is no grep, linting step, or doc-test reference.","ABSENCE: no AC verify step references either docs file by path or by a tooling check."],"finding":"The Files section lists `docs/event-schema.md` and `docs/output-schemas.md` as deliverables, but no AC verify step confirms that the docs were updated — only pytest commands and `gen_types --check` are specified. The docs deliverable is effectively unverifiable as written.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fa5041e5669e8f447","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Files section (docs/event-schema.md, docs/output-schemas.md) vs. Acceptance Criteria (AC6)","norm_id":"n827e8a587ac1e2ad","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["An implementer ships the code changes but forgets to update the docs; CI passes because no verify step checks the docs; auditors later find the public documentation does not reflect the implemented enum."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add an explicit verify step (pytest path or filter) to one of the ACs (likely AC4 or AC6) that runs the runtime/schema vocabulary-drift contract test described in the What section.","cohort":["COH","E1","T5d"],"criteria":["E1"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["What: 'Add the matching runtime constant plus validate_creation_channel(...) helper to src/rebar/reducer/_version.py and a contract test that prevents runtime/schema vocabulary drift.'","AC6 verify step lists test_schema_ticket_state.py, test_schema_outputs.py, test_schema_coverage.py — none of these names corresponds to a vocabulary-drift contract test for _version.py.","ABSENCE: no AC says 'prove with ... test_schema_vocabulary.py' or similar."],"finding":"The What section describes 'a contract test that prevents runtime/schema vocabulary drift' as a distinct deliverable, but no AC's verify command explicitly runs or names this contract test — it is not referenced in `test_creation_channel.py` filters nor in the contract-test paths listed in AC6.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f595dd9dc889fd1ab","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"What section ('contract test that prevents runtime/schema vocabulary drift') vs. Acceptance Criteria (all ACs)","norm_id":"n15cf2dfd4fb3a0ef","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["Implementer writes the vocabulary-drift contract test in _version.py or a new file, but it is never executed as part of acceptance verification, so drift can reoccur silently."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add an explicit rollback/back-out plan (e.g., 'revert create_core signature to accept optional channel defaulting to python, re-deploy with the old schema' or an expand-contract sequence: first release create_core with optional channel→required in a follow-up) so the change is safely reversible if regressions surface.","cohort":["T2","T4","T7"],"criteria":["T4"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["'Make composer.create_core require an internal keyword-only concrete channel and validate it before writing'","'New local writers reject unknown or values outside the closed enum' (AC line 4)","No rollback, back-out, or expand-contract sequence appears anywhere in the plan","T4 criterion: 'The remedy is an explicit rollback/back-out plan or expand-contract — acknowledgement alone is insufficient'"],"finding":"The plan makes `create_core` require a new keyword-only `creation_channel` parameter (an internal but real API break) and introduces runtime rejection of off-vocabulary values in all new local writers, yet provides no explicit rollback/back-out plan or expand-contract sequence if these changes cause regressions in production or undocumented call sites.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f1e0fcbf43f8f9d76","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"What section: 'Make composer.create_core require an internal keyword-only concrete channel'; Files: src/rebar/_commands/composer.py","norm_id":"nd770c7c1b5290574","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["An undocumented internal caller of create_core not listed in the Files section begins raising validation errors in production after deploy.","The new rejection semantics break an integration test suite that passes synthetic channel values, requiring a quick revert with no documented path.","A partial deploy (e.g., composer.py updated but _lib_writes.py not yet deployed) leaves the system in an inconsistent state with no rollback procedure."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Add a 'Rollback' subsection: 'If post-deploy validation rejections surface unexpected callers, revert by (1) making creation_channel optional with default python in create_core, (2) re-deploying, (3) auditing remaining callers before re-enabling strict validation.' Alternatively, structure the story as expand-contract: Phase 1 adds optional channel (no rejection), Phase 2 makes it required after all callers are confirmed.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add an ADR or CLAUDE.md entry capturing the explicit boundary-threading decision (interface supplies channel, core validates it; stack inspection and global context were rejected) so future entry-boundary additions follow the same contract.","cohort":["T5b","T5e","T9"],"criteria":["T5e"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["'Explicit boundary threading is chosen because the interface knows the channel and the shared core does not. It is simpler and more testable than stack inspection or context-local state'","Files list includes docs/event-schema.md and docs/output-schemas.md but no ADR or CLAUDE.md update","ABSENCE: no ADR / CLAUDE.md / design-doc file mentioned in the Files section for this architectural decision"],"finding":"The plan articulates a novel architectural decision — explicit boundary threading (interface-knows-channel, core-does-not) as the attribution strategy across CLI/MCP/Python entry points — but does not persist this decision in a durable design artifact such as an ADR, CLAUDE.md entry, or design-doc section. The only record is in the ephemeral plan text, so future maintainers adding a new entry boundary (e.g., a REST API or webhook) have no canonical document explaining why stack inspection and global context were rejected.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f36deba2d1a1e86ba","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Approach Rationale section; Files list (no ADR or CLAUDE.md entry present)","norm_id":"n4316fb2fb49fee38","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["A future contributor adds a REST API entry boundary and, lacking a design doc, defaults to stack inspection or a global context variable — violating the pattern this story establishes.","A reviewer of story e622 (Jira inbound) is unsure why the inbound_translate path bypasses create_core rather than passing a 'jira' channel through it — the rationale lives only in this plan's prose."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Create docs/adr/NNNN-creation-channel-attribution.md (or append to CLAUDE.md under an 'Attribution Patterns' heading) with: (1) the decision — explicit keyword threading; (2) rejected alternatives — call-stack inspection, threading.local/contextvars; (3) consequences — every new public entry point must pass a concrete channel value; (4) the out-of-scope seam (inbound_translate bypasses create_core and is handled in e622).","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Specify the exception type raised by validate_creation_channel (e.g., ValueError, a domain-specific ChannelError), and document where CLI and MCP boundaries catch and translate it into a user-facing error message or structured error response.","cohort":["E3","F4","T6"],"criteria":["T6"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["'every local live writer rejects unknown or off-vocabulary values' — no exception type, catch site, or user-visible message specified","AC #4: 'New local writers reject unknown or values outside the closed enum' — proves behavior required but does not name the error surface at CLI/MCP boundary","ABSENCE: no mention of what CLI users or MCP callers observe when validation fails (exception class, exit code, error response shape)"],"finding":"The plan introduces validate_creation_channel() and states new local writers reject invalid values, but does not specify the error contract: which exception type is raised, whether it is caught and translated into a user-facing message at CLI/MCP boundaries, or whether it propagates as an unhandled traceback to the end user.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f9ad158e062967c7f","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"What section (validate_creation_channel helper) and Files: src/rebar/_commands/composer.py, src/rebar/reducer/_version.py","norm_id":"n0b597693e807cb52","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["A programming error (e.g., a new interface that forgets to set the channel) passes an invalid value to create_core; the unhandled exception produces a raw Python traceback at the CLI instead of a clean error message","An MCP client receives an unstructured error rather than a typed MCP error response when the channel value is invalid"],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"In the What or Files section, add: 'validate_creation_channel raises ValueError with a descriptive message; CLI error handling in composer.py catches it and exits with a non-zero code and a human-readable message; MCP boundary translates it into a structured MCP error response. The contract test asserts both the exception type and the translated output.'","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add an AC (or extend AC6's proof command) that explicitly runs the runtime/schema vocabulary-drift contract test for `validate_creation_channel` in `reducer/_version.py`, so the synchronisation guarantee cannot be silently dropped.","cohort":["E5","G5"],"criteria":["E5"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["What section states: 'a contract test that prevents runtime/schema vocabulary drift'","AC4 proof: `uv run pytest -q tests/interfaces/facades/test_creation_channel.py -k \"invalid or legacy\"` — exercises rejection behavior but not the runtime-vs-schema vocabulary synchronisation","AC6 proof lists `tests/interfaces/contracts/test_schema_ticket_state.py`, `test_schema_outputs.py`, `test_schema_coverage.py` but no contract test for `_version.py` vocabulary matching the enum in `common.schema.json`","Files section lists no dedicated contract test file for `_version.py` vocabulary drift"],"finding":"The vocabulary-drift contract test for the `validate_creation_channel` helper in `reducer/_version.py` (mentioned in the What section as preventing runtime/schema drift) is not anchored to any Acceptance Criterion or named test target — it could be silently omitted and all ACs would still pass green.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f0b2d2c33fbc42daf","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"What section (contract test paragraph) vs. AC4 and AC6 proof commands; Files: tests/interfaces/contracts/ test list","norm_id":"na2232ef0dc061f5b","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["A developer adds a new value to `common.schema.json` but forgets to update the runtime constant in `_version.py`; no AC-linked test catches the drift, all ACs pass, and the validator silently rejects the new valid value at runtime."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Extend AC6 or add a new AC: 'The runtime vocabulary in `reducer/_version.py` matches the enum in `common.schema.json` exactly. Prove with `uv run pytest -q tests/interfaces/contracts/test_creation_channel_vocabulary.py`.' and add `tests/interfaces/contracts/test_creation_channel_vocabulary.py` to the Files list.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.75,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Replace `JIRA_BIND` with the actual event type name(s) that bind a local ticket to a Jira issue (verify against `KNOWN_EVENT_TYPES` in `_version.py` and the reconciler codebase), or remove the phantom name and replace with a note that binding events are handled by the Jira story; update both the 'What' section immutability rule and AC line 5 accordingly.","cohort":["E4"],"criteria":["E4"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Grep for 'JIRA_BIND' across entire repo returns zero matches in source files","KNOWN_EVENT_TYPES in src/rebar/reducer/_version.py contains: CREATE, STATUS, COMMENT, LINK, UNLINK, BRIDGE_ALERT, REVERT, EDIT, FILE_IMPACT, VERIFY_COMMANDS, SIGNATURE, ARCHIVED, SNAPSHOT, WORKFLOW_RUN, WORKFLOW_STEP, COMMITS, TAG_DELTA, KEY_ADD, KEY_REVOKE — no JIRA_BIND","Plan's 'What' section asserts: 'Reducer processors for EDIT, STATUS, LINK, JIRA_BIND, and every other non-CREATE event ignore any creation_channel key'","AC line 5 test uses `-k immutable` and explicitly names JIRA_BIND as a type to test"],"finding":"`JIRA_BIND` is named as an existing event type/processor in the plan's 'What' section and AC line 5, but it does not exist anywhere in the codebase — it is absent from `KNOWN_EVENT_TYPES` in `_version.py`, from `_processors.py`, and from any file in the repository.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fde5c3c6d385b4ba3","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"What section: 'Reducer processors for EDIT, STATUS, LINK, JIRA_BIND, and every other non-CREATE event'; AC line 5: 'EDIT, STATUS, LINK, JIRA_BIND, plus arbitrary non-CREATE payloads cannot replace creation_channel after genesis'","norm_id":"n8006e638fa9fa6e7","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["An implementer writing the immutability test for `-k immutable` will test against JIRA_BIND events that can never be produced by the real event system, creating a test that passes vacuously or never exercises a real code path","The immutability guarantee is stated as covering JIRA_BIND but no such processor exists or will be written under this story — the coverage claim is hollow","If a future story introduces a JIRA_BIND event type with a different name, the immutability rule will have no processor-level enforcement for it"],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"The relevant binding operation appears to be handled by the `SNAPSHOT` event (which the reconciler uses to persist Jira-bound state) or by the `SYNC` / `PRECONDITIONS` non-replay types. Audit `_NON_REPLAY_KNOWN_TYPES` and the reconciler's `apply_inbound.py` to identify the correct event type name, then use that name in the immutability rule and AC. If no single binding event type applies, replace the example with `SNAPSHOT` (which is in `KNOWN_EVENT_TYPES`) or simply write 'any non-CREATE event' without listing JIRA_BIND by name.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Remove `JIRA_BIND` from the AC5 immutability list (or add e622 as a `depends_on` and note that the JIRA_BIND guard is e622's responsibility), since no `JIRA_BIND` event type exists in the codebase or in any listed dependency story.","cohort":["G1G2"],"criteria":["G1G2"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["AC5 text: 'EDIT, STATUS, LINK, JIRA_BIND, plus arbitrary non-CREATE payloads cannot replace creation_channel after genesis'","grep of JIRA_BIND across all of src/rebar returns zero matches","KNOWN_EVENT_TYPES in reducer/_version.py: CREATE, STATUS, COMMENT, LINK, UNLINK, BRIDGE_ALERT, REVERT, EDIT, FILE_IMPACT, VERIFY_COMMANDS, SIGNATURE, ARCHIVED, SNAPSHOT, WORKFLOW_RUN, WORKFLOW_STEP, COMMITS, TAG_DELTA, KEY_ADD, KEY_REVOKE — no JIRA_BIND","Dependencies section: 'None. This is the foundation for the Jira/import and compaction stories.'"],"finding":"The plan references `JIRA_BIND` as a non-CREATE event type whose processor must ignore creation_channel (AC5: 'EDIT, STATUS, LINK, JIRA_BIND, plus arbitrary non-CREATE payloads cannot replace creation_channel after genesis'). No event type named JIRA_BIND exists anywhere in the codebase: it is absent from KNOWN_EVENT_TYPES in reducer/_version.py, from EVENT_TYPES in _store/event_append.py, and from the _EVENT_HANDLERS dispatch table in reducer/_replay.py. The dependency story e622 is not listed as a depends_on, so this symbol cannot be treated as 'created by a dependency'.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f41514ea930377e21","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Acceptance Criteria AC5 and the 'What' section ('JIRA_BIND')","norm_id":"n6c7fad0912f846b2","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["A reviewer or implementer tries to guard against JIRA_BIND overwriting creation_channel in the reducer, but the event type does not exist, making the guard unreachable dead code or impossible to test.","AC5's pytest -k 'immutable' test would need to fabricate a JIRA_BIND event with no existing fixture or factory, causing the test to be either skipped or written against a phantom event type name."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Change AC5 to list only event types that actually exist: 'EDIT, STATUS, LINK, UNLINK, BRIDGE_ALERT, REVERT, FILE_IMPACT, VERIFY_COMMANDS, SIGNATURE, ARCHIVED, plus arbitrary non-CREATE payloads cannot replace creation_channel after genesis. JIRA_BIND and import-sourced variants are covered by the dependent e622 story.'","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add an explicit note to the Scope/Dependencies section that the `import` enum value is reserved but will emit no writes until a follow-on story wires `_io/import_ndjson.py` to pass `creation_channel='import'`, so auditors are not surprised when querying for `import`-channeled tickets returns zero results.","cohort":["G1G2"],"criteria":["G1G2"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["import_ndjson.py line 229: 'local = create_ticket(repo_root=rr, **_provenance.create_kwargs(rec))'","Plan 'What': 'Add the canonical creation-channel enum to … with exactly cli, mcp, python, jira, import, unknown'","Plan 'Scope OUT': 'NDJSON import'","Plan 'What': 'Internal automation that directly calls the public library is truthfully python'"],"finding":"The plan's canonical enum includes six values (cli, mcp, python, jira, import, unknown), but `_io/import_ndjson.py` — the NDJSON import writer — calls `rebar.create_ticket` (the public Python API) which will default to `creation_channel='python'`. The plan explicitly scopes NDJSON import OUT, meaning imported tickets will be silently tagged `python`, not `import`. The `import` enum value will therefore be unreachable and untestable from this story, yet it is written into the canonical schema and generated types. This is an unenumerated consumer outside the Files list that is behaviorally affected.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fa4bdca11cf171294","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Scope section ('OUT: … NDJSON import') and 'What' section (six-value enum)","norm_id":"n9372f661418d8382","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["An auditor queries creation_channel='import' to identify imported tickets but finds zero results because import_ndjson.py uses the python default, making 'import' a dead enum value in production.","A schema test validates the 'import' value exists in the enum, but no code path in this story or any dependent story (e622 covers Jira inbound only) actually writes it via create_core."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.6,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Specify in the reducer plan that process_edit (and any other non-CREATE processor handling a fields-map) must actively skip `creation_channel` (e.g., add it to an explicit denylist in process_edit, or keep creation_channel out of make_initial_state so the 'not in state' guard blocks it until CREATE seeds it — then document how CREATE seeds it without it being in the initial state baseline).","cohort":["G6"],"criteria":["G6"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["process_edit (line 493): 'for field_name, new_value in fields.items(): if field_name not in state: continue ... state[field_name] = new_value' — once creation_channel is in state, this loop will overwrite it","Plan: 'EDIT, STATUS, LINK, JIRA_BIND, and every other non-CREATE event ignore any creation_channel key in their payload; a mutation cannot overwrite genesis provenance' — no named mechanism prevents a raw EDIT event's fields dict from including creation_channel","composer._EDIT_FIELDS = ('title', 'priority', 'assignee', 'ticket_type', 'description', 'parent') — user-level gate only, does not protect against events written outside composer.edit_core"],"finding":"process_edit's 'if field_name not in state' guard does NOT protect creation_channel once it is seeded into state by process_create. Any EDIT event whose data.fields dict includes a creation_channel key will overwrite it, because the key IS present in state post-CREATE. The plan says EDIT 'ignores any creation_channel key' but names no mechanism: the user-facing gate (_EDIT_FIELDS allowlist in composer.py) blocks library/CLI callers but not raw event files written directly (e.g., by Jira inbound via _write_event_file, or by a hand-crafted event). The plan must specify that process_edit (and any other non-CREATE processor that iterates state fields) explicitly skips creation_channel, or explain why the user-facing allowlist is sufficient for ALL writers.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f1862b2719671be79","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"What section / reducer/_processors.py process_edit / AC line 'EDIT, STATUS, LINK, JIRA_BIND, plus arbitrary non-CREATE payloads cannot replace creation_channel after genesis'","norm_id":"nff6f855d28d56b0f","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["A Jira inbound _write_event_file('EDIT', {'fields': {'creation_channel': 'jira'}}) would overwrite the genesis value on any ticket that had one set.","A future inbound or migration path that writes EDIT events directly bypasses the composer allowlist and accidentally clobbers the immutable field."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Either: (a) exclude `creation_channel` from `make_initial_state` so the 'if field_name not in state' guard in process_edit blocks it before CREATE fires, and have process_create use `state.setdefault` or direct assignment — but this breaks if SNAPSHOT replays (which pre-seeds from compiled_state); OR (b) add `creation_channel` to an explicit skip set in process_edit (analogous to how `tags` is handled specially): `_EDIT_SKIP = frozenset({'creation_channel'})` checked before applying the field.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.6,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Consider deferring `creation_channel_inferred` schema field and TypedDict entry to story e622 (the Jira/import story that will actually produce the inference case), so both the schema field and its writer land together; alternatively, add an explicit note in the schema describing exactly which code path sets it and under what conditions it appears.","cohort":["G6"],"criteria":["G6"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan: 'Encode the marker as {\"const\": true}; recorded and unknown projections omit it.' — within this story's scope all projections are 'recorded', so the field is always omitted.","Plan: 'The Jira inbound CREATE seam bypasses create_core (inbound_translate writes raw event files directly) and is OUT of scope here; the dependent Jira/import story e622 wires that seam to the same helper.' — the only path where inference would be needed is deferred.","ABSENCE: no writer in any in-scope file (_lib_writes.py, _mcp_writes.py, composer.py, identity.py, session_log.py, idea.py) would set creation_channel_inferred."],"finding":"The plan adds `creation_channel_inferred: {\"const\": true}` to ticket_state.schema.json and generated TicketState types, but within this story's scope there is no writer that ever sets this field. Every local creation path (CLI/MCP/Python) gets an explicit concrete channel value, so the inference marker is never `true`. The only likely writer — the Jira/import inbound path (story e622) — is explicitly OUT of scope. Shipping the schema field in this story creates a dead contract element: the field appears in the schema and TypedDict but is never populated by any code path this story delivers.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f87d9d826582b962f","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"What section ('Add optional public schema fields creation_channel and creation_channel_inferred to ticket_state.schema.json') / AC line 'ticket_state JSON Schema, generated TicketState types... expose the same six-value enum and true-only optional inference marker'","norm_id":"nff289da04c8fc4f5","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["Schema consumers (e.g., validators, MCP type checkers) see a documented field that is always absent in practice — misleading contract.","The TypedDict includes creation_channel_inferred but no code in this story sets it, so it is effectively dead code in the generated types file."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add the definition of LEGACY_JIRA_AUTHOR=\"reconciler\" and LEGACY_JIRA_ENV_ID=\"reconciler\" to the leaf's What and to the reducer/_version.py file-impact entry, so e622's absolute-import seam has a defined foundation when it lands.","cohort":["G7"],"criteria":["G7"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Parent arch decision: 'Define both constants in src/rebar/reducer/_version.py. inbound_translate._event_meta performs the absolute package import (from rebar.reducer._version import LEGACY_JIRA_AUTHOR, LEGACY_JIRA_ENV_ID) inside its function body'","Leaf What: 'Add the matching runtime constant plus validate_creation_channel(...) helper to src/rebar/reducer/_version.py' — singular 'runtime constant' suggests only the closed-enum vocabulary, not the two legacy inference constants","Leaf Files: reducer/_version.py described as 'canonical runtime vocabulary and state projection' — no mention of LEGACY_JIRA_AUTHOR or LEGACY_JIRA_ENV_ID","6fe2 owns the only planned _version.py changes; e622's dependency story (e622 depends_on 6fe2) presupposes these constants already exist in _version.py when e622 lands"],"finding":"The leaf omits defining LEGACY_JIRA_AUTHOR and LEGACY_JIRA_ENV_ID constants in reducer/_version.py, even though the parent's Architecture Decisions explicitly place those definitions there and child e622 depends on importing them from that file.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fb67a655588b957b0","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Leaf What section / src/rebar/reducer/_version.py file entry; Parent Architecture Decisions: 'Define both constants in src/rebar/reducer/_version.py'","norm_id":"n968ba533ae8aa15a","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["e622 attempts to import LEGACY_JIRA_AUTHOR/LEGACY_JIRA_ENV_ID from rebar.reducer._version but they were never defined, causing an ImportError or forcing e622 to add constants to a file it doesn't 'own' per the decomposition.","The isolated spec-load contract test that e622 plans to add (pinning these constants) would have no target if 6fe2 didn't define them — breaking e622's AC#8 from the outset."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"In the leaf's What section, extend the reducer/_version.py bullet to read: 'Add the matching runtime constants (validate_creation_channel vocabulary plus LEGACY_JIRA_AUTHOR=\"reconciler\" and LEGACY_JIRA_ENV_ID=\"reconciler\") to src/rebar/reducer/_version.py — the Jira/import story imports these via the absolute package path.' Update the Files entry for reducer/_version.py to: 'canonical runtime vocabulary, legacy Jira inference constants, and state projection.'","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Document (in the plan or in a rollback runbook) what `creation_channel` projection looks like after a rollback, and assert that a rollback followed by compaction cannot permanently lose the field — either by adding `creation_channel` to `_snapshot_strip_keys()` exclusions rationale, ensuring old binaries tolerate the key passively via process_snapshot's blanket restore, or by explicitly pinning the compaction guard until the feature is stable.","cohort":["T11"],"criteria":["T11"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan states: 'SNAPSHOT durability' is listed under OUT of scope.","process_create in the existing codebase explicitly copies only known keys (source_id, source_created_at, etc.) into state — an old binary replaying a new CREATE event with creation_channel would silently drop the field.","T11 criterion: 'the plan must assert on the schema STATE AFTER rollback, not merely that rollback exits 0'.","No plan section describes the rollback state or documents the projection gap between raw events and compiled state on old binaries."],"finding":"The plan does not assert the schema/projected-state after a rollback: if the new code is reverted, tickets already written with `creation_channel` in CREATE.data will silently lose that field in projected state (process_create in old binaries does not copy it), creating a divergence between raw event files and compiled state. The plan says 'SNAPSHOT durability' is OUT OF SCOPE but does not assert that the store remains consistent or describe the post-rollback field state.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f86249f71506a4774","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Scope section (OUT: SNAPSHOT durability) and Files: reducer/_processors.py","norm_id":"nb7cc339ad3ad4fe1","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["Feature is deployed, new tickets are written with creation_channel=cli/mcp/python in CREATE.data, then the code is rolled back to pre-change binary. Old process_create ignores the key; show/list/search return no creation_channel — diverging from what the raw event file records.","A compaction run by old code after rollback writes a SNAPSHOT without creation_channel in compiled_state; re-deploying the new code restores from that SNAPSHOT and also loses the field permanently (the raw CREATE event file has been retired)."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Add a plan section asserting: 'After rollback, `creation_channel` is present in raw CREATE event files and will be projected correctly when the new code is re-deployed. To prevent permanent loss via compaction-on-rollback, do not run compact-all between rollback and re-deploy, OR confirm that process_snapshot's blanket `for key, value in compiled_state.items()` restore means a SNAPSHOT written by new code (containing creation_channel) is safely restored by old code (since old process_snapshot does the same blanket copy).'","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Specify that `ticket_state.schema.json`'s `creation_channel` field MUST use `$ref: 'common.schema.json#/$defs/creation_channel'` (or the equivalent inline enum identical to the common def) so the closed-enum contract is enforced at schema level, not only by the runtime validator.","cohort":["T8"],"criteria":["T8"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan says: 'Add the canonical creation-channel enum to src/rebar/schemas/common.schema.json with exactly cli, mcp, python, jira, import, unknown'","Plan says: 'Add optional public schema fields creation_channel and creation_channel_inferred to ticket_state.schema.json'","ABSENCE: plan never says ticket_state.schema.json should use $ref: 'common.schema.json#/$defs/creation_channel'; existing ticket_type, ticket_status, priority, and relation fields in ticket_state.schema.json all use $ref to common.schema.json definitions (verified in file)"],"finding":"The plan adds `creation_channel` as an optional field to `ticket_state.schema.json` but never specifies whether it uses a `$ref` to the canonical `common.schema.json#/$defs/creation_channel` definition or defines its own inline enum. Without an explicit `$ref`, an implementor may write a plain `{\"type\": \"string\"}` field, allowing vocabulary drift between the ticket-state output schema and the canonical enum — the very problem the contract test is meant to prevent.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f5439f2d7c3d94606","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Plan § What / Files: src/rebar/schemas/ticket_state.schema.json","norm_id":"n8134d6f84696ff73","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["An implementor adds `creation_channel: {type: string}` to ticket_state.schema.json without a $ref, schema contract tests pass for generation but fail to catch a value added to common.schema.json that was never reflected in the output schema.","gen_types generates TicketState with creation_channel typed as plain str instead of a Literal from the enum, losing the closed-enum guarantee in generated Python types."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"In ticket_state.schema.json, add: `\"creation_channel\": { \"$ref\": \"common.schema.json#/$defs/creation_channel\" }` (after the $def is added to common.schema.json). Mirror the existing pattern used for ticket_type and ticket_status.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Specify in the plan that `process_edit` (and any other non-CREATE processor that touches state fields) must explicitly exclude `creation_channel` from the writable field set — e.g. by adding it to an `_IMMUTABLE_KEYS` frozenset or guarding it with `if field_name in _EDIT_FIELDS` (which already excludes it at the write layer, but the reducer must also guard on replay for historical/imported events).","cohort":["T8"],"criteria":["T8"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan says: 'EDIT, STATUS, LINK, JIRA_BIND, and every other non-CREATE event ignore any creation_channel key in their payload; a mutation cannot overwrite genesis provenance'","process_edit code: `for field_name, new_value in fields.items(): if field_name not in state: continue ... state[field_name] = new_value` — if creation_channel is in state, this WILL overwrite it","ABSENCE: the plan never specifies adding creation_channel to a denylist in process_edit, nor does it say creation_channel should not be seeded into make_initial_state"],"finding":"The plan states that 'EDIT, STATUS, LINK, JIRA_BIND, and every other non-CREATE event ignore any creation_channel key in their payload' and that 'a mutation cannot overwrite genesis provenance', but does not specify WHERE this enforcement lives in the reducer. `process_edit` (in `_processors.py`) currently applies LWW for every key in `state` that appears in `data['fields']`. If `creation_channel` is present in `make_initial_state` or is set by `process_create`, it will be in `state`, and a malformed EDIT event carrying `fields.creation_channel` WILL overwrite it via the existing `process_edit` loop — unless the plan specifies adding an explicit exclusion guard inside `process_edit`.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fae9676a9ad9b05c7","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Plan § What / Files: src/rebar/reducer/_processors.py; reducer/_processors.py lines 485-510 (process_edit)","norm_id":"n8966c6b6f0814502","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["A crafted EDIT event with fields.creation_channel='unknown' rewrites genesis provenance on a ticket created via CLI.","An inbound JIRA_BIND event (or a future event type) that happens to include a creation_channel key silently clobbers the auditable genesis record."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Add to the _processors.py spec: 'process_edit must skip any field_name in an explicit _GENESIS_IMMUTABLE_KEYS frozenset (minimally {\"creation_channel\"}); this guard sits in the reducer, independently of the write-path _EDIT_FIELDS check, so replay of any historical or imported EDIT event cannot overwrite genesis provenance.'","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Specify the failure contract for `validate_creation_channel`: it should raise `CommandError(error_code='invalid_creation_channel', ...)` (mirroring the `invalid_ticket_type` pattern) so the MCP and CLI layers emit a consistent structured error envelope.","cohort":["T8"],"criteria":["T8"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan says: 'create_core calls this helper, so every local live writer rejects unknown or off-vocabulary values'","Plan says: 'The Jira inbound CREATE seam bypasses create_core … and is OUT of scope here'","ABSENCE: no error code string (e.g. 'invalid_creation_channel'), no CommandError vs ValueError specification, no exit code or MCP error response shape is named for this failure path","Existing create_core uses CommandError with named error_code (e.g. 'invalid_ticket_type') and specific exit codes — the new validator must follow the same pattern but the plan does not say so"],"finding":"The plan says `validate_creation_channel(...)` is called by `create_core` so 'every local live writer rejects unknown or off-vocabulary values', but it never specifies the failure mode: what exception type is raised, what error code is emitted, and what exit code/HTTP response the caller receives. This is a processing-protocol gap that leaves the error path unspecified for an executor implementing the validation helper.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f6e426a8bd3b432b6","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Plan § What; AC line 4 ('New local writers reject unknown or values outside the closed enum')","norm_id":"nc8ce476789fbe7f3","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["An MCP client passes an unexpected channel string; the MCP wrapper receives an untyped exception instead of a structured tool error.","A test asserting on the error_code string 'invalid_creation_channel' fails because the implementor chose a different code, causing the AC 'invalid' test suite to be written inconsistently."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Explicitly list `session_log.start()`, `session_log.append()`, `rebar.append_session_log()`, and `rebar.start_session_log()` as functions that must gain a `creation_channel` keyword parameter, and specify that the default is `python` and MCP callers pass `mcp`.","cohort":["T8"],"criteria":["T8"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan says: 'MCP create_ticket, create_idea, create_identity, and first-use log_session persist and return creation_channel=mcp'","Plan says: 'Thread this value explicitly through existing helper functions rather than inspecting the call stack'","session_log.py code: `def start(*, summary=None, relates_to=None, discovered_from=None, repo_root=None)` and `def append(entry, *, summary=None, ...)` — neither signature carries creation_channel","ABSENCE: plan lists `_commands/idea.py and session_log.py: explicit helper attribution` in Files but never names session_log.start / session_log.append as needing updated signatures, only that 'session-log library helpers accept an internal creation_channel keyword defaulting to python'"],"finding":"The plan says MCP `log_session` (first-use path) persists `creation_channel=mcp`, but the call chain is MCP `log_session` → `rebar.append_session_log` → `session_log.append()` → `session_log.start()` → `create_core()`. The plan says to 'thread this value explicitly through existing helper functions', but it does not specify that `session_log.start()` and `session_log.append()` must gain a `creation_channel` keyword parameter. These are intermediate layers in a file the plan lists (`_commands/session_log.py`) but whose function signatures are not updated in the plan's threading description. The equivalent gap exists for `_lib_writes.append_session_log` and `start_session_log`.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f3490945c452d03d3","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Plan § What / Files: src/rebar/_commands/session_log.py; src/rebar/_lib_writes.py","norm_id":"n9cf661acbe81c522","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["An implementor adds creation_channel to the MCP log_session wrapper but not to session_log.append/start, so the value is dropped before reaching create_core.","The MCP log_session AC test passes because it checks the wrapper's kwarg but the CREATE event on disk still has no creation_channel (the intermediate layer never forwarded it)."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["G1G2"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":[],"finding":"The 'What' section states 'create_core and the direct Jira CREATE seam both call this helper [validate_creation_channel]', but the Scope section explicitly marks 'Jira inbound creation' as OUT, and the actual Jira inbound CREATE path uses `_write_event_file` in `inbound_translate.py` — a completely separate code path that does not call `create_core` at all.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fdbe6a4971c174609","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"What section (second bullet); Scope section (OUT: 'Jira inbound creation'); src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/apply_inbound_records.py:145","norm_id":"nba2d2d287dfb14bd","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":[],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Remove 'and the direct Jira CREATE seam' from the second 'What' bullet, since Jira inbound creation is explicitly OUT of scope. The validate_creation_channel helper should guard only create_core (and any caller that doesn't route through it) for this story.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["T11"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":[],"finding":"The plan specifies 'A legacy CREATE with no value projects creation_channel=unknown' but does not prescribe a matching `process_snapshot` migration guard for pre-existing SNAPSHOTs. Every prior additive compiled-state field (managed_refs, attestations, keyring) has an explicit guard in `process_snapshot` to re-derive or default the field when absent from compiled_state. Without such a guard, any ticket already compacted into a SNAPSHOT before this story ships will silently omit `creation_channel` from projected state — returning neither `cli`/`mcp`/`python` nor `unknown` — contradicting the plan's own 'reduces to unknown' invariant and producing inconsistent output between compacted and non-compacted tickets.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fdd6f58702ef61c0f","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"What section ('A legacy CREATE with no value projects creation_channel=unknown'); Files section (reducer/_processors.py); Scope section ('OUT: SNAPSHOT durability')","norm_id":"n49c5b92478da5a4e","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":[],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"In `process_snapshot`, after the existing keyring migration block, add: `if 'creation_channel' not in compiled_state: state['creation_channel'] = 'unknown'`. This is the exact pattern already used for `managed_refs`, `attestations`, and `keyring` and requires no schema change.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.75,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["E4"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":[],"finding":"The plan asserts 'create_core and the direct Jira CREATE seam both call this helper [validate_creation_channel]', but the Jira inbound CREATE seam (_inbound_create_write_create_event) does NOT call create_core — it writes events directly via _write_event_file, bypassing create_core entirely. Simultaneously, the plan scopes Jira inbound creation OUT. These two statements are contradictory.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f3ffac3e8c4568527","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"What section ('create_core and the direct Jira CREATE seam both call this helper, so every live writer rejects unknown or off-vocabulary values') vs Scope OUT ('Jira inbound creation')","norm_id":"ne5594ff395d797ea","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":[],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["T1"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":[],"finding":"The plan encodes `creation_channel_inferred` as `{\"const\": true}` in ticket_state.schema.json and asserts this will produce a correctly typed field in the generated types.py, but gen_types.py is a custom generator documented to handle only `enum`→`Literal` (not `const`). If `const` is unhandled, the generator will silently emit `Any` or `bool` rather than `Literal[True]`, making the typed contract weaker than specified and potentially causing the `--check` drift-gate to pass with a wrong type.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f08f9e283d58c2e0f","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"What section / Files / AC line 6 ('Regenerate derived public types') and src/rebar/schemas/gen_types.py","norm_id":"n53bbb8e858cca943","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":[],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Add a `const` branch to gen_types.py's type-emitter (e.g., when a property schema has `\"const\": <value>`, emit `Literal[<value>]`). Alternatively, encode the marker as `{\"type\": \"boolean\"}` with a description note and accept `NotRequired[bool]` in TicketState — simpler and already handled by the generator.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.6,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["G6"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":[],"finding":"The plan does not address the SNAPSHOT migration case for creation_channel. Every other present-only additive field that survives compaction has an explicit migration guard in process_snapshot (managed_refs seeds from current state, attestations folds legacy signature, keyring re-bootstraps). A legacy SNAPSHOT written before this story (lacking creation_channel in compiled_state) will restore state without the key. The plan's legacy handling ('a legacy CREATE with no value projects creation_channel=unknown') covers only the CREATE event replay path, not the SNAPSHOT short-circuit path where pre-existing SNAPSHOTs already contain compiled_state.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"ff4bbeaebda778338","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"What section — 'Store creation_channel in CREATE.data…project it into compiled state exactly once'; Files — reducer/_processors.py (process_snapshot)","norm_id":"nbf559897acb0190f","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":[],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["T8"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":[],"finding":"The plan specifies that legacy CREATEs with no creation_channel project creation_channel=unknown, but does not specify the SNAPSHOT migration behavior — whether process_snapshot needs a guard for pre-feature SNAPSHOTs that lack creation_channel, following the established pattern for every other newly-added field (managed_refs, attestations, keyring each have explicit migration clauses in process_snapshot).","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f29c638c8fb26e68d","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"What section paragraph 5 ('A legacy CREATE with no value projects creation_channel=unknown'); reducer/_processors.py process_snapshot (lines 744-793)","norm_id":"n86493d88d01a6a59","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":[],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.75,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["E4"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":[],"finding":"The plan claims 'JIRA_BIND' is a real event type that must ignore creation_channel, but JIRA_BIND does not exist in KNOWN_EVENT_TYPES or anywhere in the codebase; the immutability AC and the reducer processor scope both reference a phantom event type.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fca868c629d3fb984","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"What section ('Reducer processors for EDIT, STATUS, LINK, JIRA_BIND...'); AC line 'EDIT, STATUS, LINK, JIRA_BIND, plus arbitrary non-CREATE payloads cannot replace creation_channel after genesis'","norm_id":"n080944b81f91743a","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":[],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Remove JIRA_BIND from both the 'What' prose and the AC. The real threat to genesis immutability is the process_edit 'field in state' guard (once creation_channel is in state, an EDIT event that names it would overwrite it); the plan should instead explicitly specify that creation_channel is excluded from _EDIT_FIELDS and the test should confirm an EDIT payload carrying creation_channel is rejected or ignored.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["G1G2"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":[],"finding":"`JIRA_BIND` is referenced as a real event type in the plan's 'What' section and AC (immutable test), but this event type does not exist anywhere in the codebase — it is absent from `KNOWN_EVENT_TYPES`, `_processors.py`, and all reconciler modules.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fdb32c63a03c1566b","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"What section ('Reducer processors for EDIT, STATUS, LINK, JIRA_BIND…'); AC line 5 ('EDIT, STATUS, LINK, JIRA_BIND…')","norm_id":"nf50247f07968b2d0","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":[],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Replace 'JIRA_BIND' with 'SNAPSHOT' (the only event that restores compiled_state wholesale and could plausibly overwrite genesis provenance) and verify the reducer's `process_snapshot` migration path is addressed. Or simply use 'EDIT' and 'BRIDGE_ALERT' as representative non-CREATE events in the AC.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null}],"impact_model_version":"plan-v3","material_fingerprint":"8952d9ee2ecbe1ea","metrics":{"claim_path":"no-llm/no-network (structural; the fast claim check is a local HMAC verify)","det_ms":209.0,"llm_calls":30,"llm_ms":538317.8,"total_ms":538672.5,"verify_requests":19},"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","regver":"b293b9a55de591cc","runner":"pydantic_ai","schema":"plan_review_result_v2","ticket_id":"6fe2-ab22-c231-4a41","ticket_type":"story","verdict":"PASS","verified_at_sha":"faa40e7b07b1ebfd7f0a12e122e9017b0cdd0b35"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"REVIEW_RESULT","timestamp":1784267487454471001,"uuid":"1088196e-5479-4c5a-b409-abd0f28a5176"}